t5739.text: Many people omit “¿” when writing Spanish emails or tweets, but it’s never the case in more formal, elaborate documents or posts and, in short, omitting “¿” is incorrect and unkind to the reader.

t5740.text: If you don’t have the “¿” in the second sentence, you as a reader could begin reading it as an affirmative instead of a question. And the see the “?”. And then annoyingly go back and re-read.

t5741.text: In that sense, “¿” plays the same role as in English flipping the verb and pronoun order.

t5742.text: For questions longer than “tú has comido?”, using only the final “?” would be ambiguous for a reader. That’s why we also open the question, “¿tú has comido?”.

t5743.text: So, “You have eaten” is written as “tú has comido”, and question “have you eaten” is, as well, “tú has comido”. If we only used in written Spanish the final question mark, you should have to see the end of the sentence to detect the question.

t5744.text: Spanish language facts: this “¿” is not an “upside down question mark”, but an opening question mark in Spanish. In Spanish, the verb and pronoun don’t change places when asking questions.
